description: TO RECOMMIT TO THE COMM. OF THE WHOLE THE PRESIDENT'S MESSAGE ON FOREIGN RELATIONS, PUBLIC DEFENSE, REVENUE, COMMERCIAL LAWS, FOREIGN TRADE LICENSE, AND SPANISH AMERICAN COLONIES, SO AS TO CONSIDER CERTAIN PAPERS WHICH WERE NOT PREVIOUSLY AVAILABLE. (P. 38)
TO HAVE READ THE DOCUMENTS WHICH WERE SUBMITTED WITH THE PRESIDENT'S MESSAGE.  (P. 341)
TO ORDER ENGROSSMENT OF H.R. 3 (APP. DEC. 16, 1811) TO PROVIDE A PENSION FOR ABRAHAM WHIPPLE, FOR INJURIES RECEIVED WHILE A CAPTAIN IN THE NAVY DURING THE REVOLUTIONARY WAR.  (P. 355-1)
TO POSTPONE UNTIL FIRST MONDAY IN FEBRUARY THE RESOLUTION TO LAY ADDITIONAL DUTIES ON COARSE MANUFACTURES OF FLAX, HEMP AND COTTON.

TO CONCUR IN AN AMENDMENT TO H.R. 8 (APP. DEC. 21, 1811, 2 STAT 669) A BILL APPORTION REPRESENTATIVES AMONG THE SEVERAL STATES, SO AS TO SET 35,000 AS THE NUMBER OF INHABITANTS TO EACH REPRESENTATIVE.
TO AMEND H.R. 8 TO SET 40,000 INHABITANTS AS REQUIRED FOR EACH REPRESENTATIVE.  (P. 365-1)
TO AMEND H.R. 8 TO SET 37,000 INHABITANTS AS REQUIRED FOR EACH REPRESENTATIVE.  (P. 365)
TO RECOMMIT H.R. 8 TO COMMITTEE.  (P. 367)
TO CONSIDER THE RESOLUTION CONCERNING ADDITIONAL DUTIES ON CERTAIN IMPORTED ARTICLES.  (P. 371)

TO CONCUR IN THE REPORT OF COMMITTEE CONCERNING THE PETITION OF JOHN TALIAFERRO, CONTESTING THE ELECTION OF JOHN HUNGERSFORD, OF VIRGINIA, WHICH REPORT GIVES THE PRESENT REPRESENTATIVE REASONABLE TIME TO PROCURE TESTIMONY RELATIVE TO HIS ELECTION, AND TOGIVE THE COMMITTEE POWER TO EXAMINE WITNESSES

TO RECOMMIT THE REPORT OF THE COMM. OF ELECTIONS CONCERNING THE CONTESTED ELECTION OF JOHN HUNGERFORD, SAID REPORT TO GIVE HUNGERFORD TIME TO PROCURE DEFENSIVE TESTIMONY, AND TO GIVE THE COMMITTEE POWER TO EXAMINE WITNESSES.  (P. 394-1)
TO PASS THE RESOLUTION THAT JOHN HUNGERFORD, THE PRESENT REPRESENTATIVE FROM VIRGINIA, IS NOT ENTITLED TO A SEAT IN THE HOUSE.
TO PASS THE RESOLUTION THAT JOHN TALIAFERRO IS ENTITLED TO A SEAT IN THE HOUSE.
TO POSTPONE UNTIL TOMORROW FURTHER CONSIDERATION OF H.R. 8.
TO CONCUR IN THE SENATE AMENDMENT TO H.R. 8, TO REDUCE THE NUMBER OF INHABITANTS REQUIRED FOR EACH REPRESENTATIVE FROM 37,000 TO 35,000.
TO CONCUR IN THE RESOLUTION TO FILL UP THE RANKS OF THE MILITARY ESTABLISHMENT, TO PROLONG THE ENLISTMENT OF TROOPS, AND TO GIVE A BOUNTY OF LAND TO ENCOURAGE ENLISTMENTS.
TO ADJOURN, MOTION MADE DURING CONSIDERATION OF A RESOLUTION TO PERMIT MERCHANT VESSELS TO ARM.
TO CONCUR IN THE RESOLUTION TO RAISE A CERTAIN NUMBER OF TROOPS TO SERVE FOR THREE YEARS, AND TO GIVE A BOUNTY OF LAND TO ENCOURAGE ENLISTMENTS.
TO CONCUR IN THE RESOLUTION TO AUTHORIZE THE PRESIDENT TO ACCEPT THE SERVICE OF VOLUNTEERS, NO MORE THAN 50,000, TO BE HELD IN MILITARY SERVICE.
TO CONCUR IN THE RESOLUTION TO AUTHORIZE THE PRESIDENT TO ORDER OUT, FROM TIME TO TIME, SUCH DETACHMENT OF THE MILITIA AS NECESSARY.
TO CONCUR IN THE RESOLUTION THAT ALL NAVY VESSELS NOT NOW IN SERVICE AND NEEDING REPAIR, BE IMMEDIATELY FITTED UP AND PUT IN COMMISSION.
TO POSTPONE THE ORDER OF THE DAY, WHICH IS THE COMMITTEE REPORT ON H.R. 8.
TO RECEDE FROM DISAGREEMENT TO THE SENATE AMENDMENT TO H.R. 8, WHICH WOULD MAKE EACH REPRESENTATIVE EQUAL 35,000 INHABITANTS.
TO AMEND THE RESOLUTION TO ALLOW MERCHANT VESSELS TO ARM IN SELF-DEFENSE AGAINST ALL UNLAWFUL PROCEEDINGS TOWARD THEM ON THE HIGH SEAS, TO ELIMINATE THE PHRASE "SELF-DEFENSE".
TO AMEND THE MERCHANT VESSELS RESOLUTION BY CHANGING THE ENTIRE RESOLUTION TO: "AUTHORIZE MERCHANT VESSELS OF THE U.S. TO ARM UNDER PROPER REGULATIONS TO BE PRESCRIBED BY LAW."
TO CONCUR IN THE AMENDED MERCHANT VESSELS RESOLUTION WHICH WOULD PREVENT SAID VESSELS FROM ACTING IN SELF DEFENSE BUT WHICH WOULD ALLOW THEM TO ARM.
TO PASS S. 5, (APP. DEC. 24, 1811) TO COMPLETE THE MILITARY ESTABLISHMENT.

TO AMEND THE RESOLUTION AMENDING THE RULES OF THE HOUSE RELATING TO PREVIOUS QUESTION, SO AS TO LIMIT EVERY MEMBER TO SPEAK ONLY ONCE WHEN THE PREVIOUS QUESTION IS ORDERED TO BE TAKEN UPON THE MAIN QUESTION BEING PUT.
TO AMEND THE RESOLUTION TO AMEND THE RULES OF THE HOUSE TO ALSO PROVIDE: "NO QUESTIONS OF CONSIDERATION SHALL BE REQUIRED UPON THE ORIGINAL MOTION."
TO ADJOURN.
TO ADJOURN; MOTION MADE DURING CONSIDERATION OF S. 6 (APP. JAN. 11, 1812) TO RAISE ADDITIONAL MILITARY FORCE.
TO AMEND S. 6 TO GIVE THE PRESIDENT FULL CONTROL OVER THE APPOINTMENT OF OFFICERS.
TO AMEND S. 6 TO ALLOW THE PRESIDENT TO MAKE ANY APPOINTMENTS REGARDING OFFICERS AS NECESSARY.
TO ORDER ENGROSSMENT OF AMENDMENTS AND THIRD READING OF S. 6.
TO PASS S. 6.
TO POSTPONE CONSIDERATION OF S. 6, AFTER THE BILL HAD BEEN RETURNED FROM THE SENATE WITH THE REQUEST THAT THE HOUSE RECEDE FROM ITS AMENDMENTS.
TO RECEDE FROM THE FIRST AMENDMENT TO S. 6 WHICH LIMITS THE APPOINTMENT OF OFFICERS TO SIX REGIMENTS.
TO RECEDE FROM THE SECOND AMENDMENT TO S. 6, THAT OFFICERS SHOULD CONTINUE IN COMMISSION ONLY AS LONG AS THE PRESIDENT DEEMS NECESSARY.
TO RECEDE FROM THE AMENDMENT TO S. 6 WHICH PROHIBITED GENERAL FIELD OR STAFF OFFICERS TO RECEIVE PAY UNTIL CALLED INTO SERVICE.
TO PASS THE RESOLUTION TO AUTHORIZE THE PRESIDENT TO EMPLOY THE REGULAR ARMY IN CONSTRUCTION OF ROADS, CANALS, ETC.
TO AMEND H.R. 32 (APP. JULY 6, 1812) TO AUTHORIZE THE PRESIDENT TO ACCEPT AND ORGANIZE CERTAIN VOLUNTEER MILITARY CORPS, TO REDUCE THE FORCE FROM FIFTY TO TWENTY THOUSAND MEN.
TO AMEND A BILL TO ESTABLISH A VOLUNTEER MILITARY CORPS (APP. FEB. 8, 1812), BY CONFINING THE ACTIVITY OF THE CORPS TO WITHIN THE U.S.
TO ORDER THIRD READING OF A BILL ESTABLISHING A VOLUNTEER MILITARY CORPS.  (FEB. 8, 1812)
TO ORDER ENGROSSMENT OF A BILL TO ESTABLISH A VOLUNTEER MILITARY CORPS.  (APP. FEB. 9, 1812)
TO PRINT 5000 COPIES OF THE REPORT OF THE SEC. OF THE TREASURY, DEALING WITH THE INCREASE OF REVENUE.
TO AMEND H.R. 24 FOR THE NAVAL ESTABLISHMENT OF ALL VESSELS BELONGING TO THE NAVY WORTHY OF REPAIR, TO FILL IN THE BLANK WITH THE SUM OF $480,000 FOR THE REPAIRS.
TO CONCUR IN THE SECOND AMENDMENT OF COMM. OF WHOLE TO H.R. 24, WHICH AMENDMENT ELIMINATES A SECTION PROVIDING FOR BUILDING 50 ADDITIONAL FRIGATES.
TO CONCUR IN THE THIRD AMENDMENT TO H.R. 24, PROVIDING TO APPROPRIATE A SUM TO DEFRAY THE COST OF TIMBER, ETC, FOR SHIP BUILDING.
TO CONCUR IN THE FOURTH AMENDMENT TO H.R. 24 TO MAKE AN APPROPRIATION OF $200,000 ANNUALLY FOR THREE YEARS RATHER THAN TO CALL FOR AN APPROPRIATION OF $440,000 AT THIS TIME.
TO AMEND H.R. 24 BY ELIMINATING THE SECTION APPROPRIATING $100,000 FOR THE BUILDING OF A DOCK YARD.
TO AMEND H.R. 24 SO TO PROVIDE FOR COMPLETION OF 74 GUN SHIPS.
TO PASS H.R. 24.
TO REQUEST THE PRESIDENT TO INFORM THE HOUSE OF INFORMATION HE HAS IN REGARDS TO THE SEIZURE OF AMERICAN SHIPS BY EUROPEAN GOVERNMENTS.

TO AMEND H.R. 37, AN ACT TO PROVIDE FOR THE NATIONAL DEFENSE BY THE ESTABLISHMENT OF A UNIFORM MILITIA, TO ELIMINATE THE SECTION PROVIDING THAT SOLDIERS BETWEEN 18 AND 21 YEARS OF AGE SHALL BE CALLED THE MINOR CLASS, AND SHALL BE CONFINED TO THEIR OWN REPECTIVE STATES, AND SHALL SERVE NO MORE THAN THREE MONTHS.
TO AMEND H.R. 37 TO AUTHORIZE THE STATE LEGISLATURES TO DELIVER THE ARMS TO THE CITIZENS, OR PRESERVE THEM FOR THEIR USE IN DEPOTS.

TO AMEND H.R. 105 (APP. FEB. 21, 1812) A BILL TO PROVIDE APPROPRIATIONS FOR THE SUPPORT OF THE GOVERNMENT FOR 1812, BY ELIMINATING THE APPROPRIATION TO INCREASE THE SALARIES OF CLERKS IN THE SEVERAL DEPARTMENTS.
TO ORDER ENGROSSMENT AND THIRD READING OF H.R. 37.
TO PASS H.R. 37.
TO PASS H.R. 25 (MAR. 10, 1812), A BILL TO PROVIDE ADDITIONAL APPROPRIATIONS FOR THE DEFENSE OF OUR MARITIMES FRONTIERS.
TO ORDER ENGROSSMENT AND THIRD READING OF H.R. 15, A BILL FOR THE RELIEF OF INFIRM, DISABLED, AND SUPERANNUATED OFFICERS OF THE U.S. ARMY.
TO ORDER ENGROSSMENT AND THIRD READING OF H.R. 55 (APP. FEB. 21, 1812) FOR THE RELIEF OF CAPTAIN SILAH BENTON.
TO CONCUR IN THE REPORT OF THE COMM. OF THE WHOLE REGARDING THE PETITION OF THE MERCHANT, STEPHAN KINGSTON, PRAYING TO BE ALLOWED THE DRAWBACK ON SUNDRY GOODS SHIPPED BY HIM TO ALGIERS.
TO PASS H.R. 15, A BILL FOR RELIEF OF THE INFIRM, DISABLED, AND SUPERANNUATED OFFICERS AND SOLDIERS OF THE U.S. ARMY.
TO AMEND H.R. 37, TO PROVIDE THAT ARMS BE DISTRIBUTED AS THE LEGISLATURES OF THE SEVERAL STATES MAY BY LAW DIRECT.
TO RECONSIDER THE AMENDMENT TO H.R. 37 TO ALLOW THE LEGISLATURES OF THE SEVERAL STATES TO DIRECT THE DISTRIBUTION OF ARMS.
TO AMEND H.R. 37 TO GIVE EACH CITIZEN OF 18 YEARS OR OLDER, POSSESSION OF A STAND OF ARMS.

TO ADOPT THE RESOLUTION THAT A COMMITTEE BE APPOINTED TO PREPARE AND REPORT A BILL AUTHORIZING THE PRESIDENT TO ORGANIZE A PROVISIONAL MILITARY FORCE OF 20,000 MEN IN ADDITION TO THE FORCE ALREADY AUTHORIZED BY LAW.
TO POSTPONE INDEFINITELY CONSIDERATION OF H.R. 37.
TO AMEND H.R. 37 SO AS TO LIMIT THE POWER GIVEN THE STATE LEGISLATURES OF DISPOSING OF ARMS.
TO ORDER ENGROSSMENT AND THIRD READING OF H.R. 37.
TO PUT THE MAIN QUESTION ON PASSAGE OF H.R. 37.
TO PASS H.R. 37.
TO CONCUR IN THE AMENDMENT OF H.R. 105 (APP. FEB. 21, 1812) TO PROVIDE APPROPRIATIONS FOR THE GOVERNMENT, TO RESTORE THE 15% ADDITIONAL COMPENSATION TO THE CLERKS.
TO CONCUR IN THE AMENDMENT TO H.R. 105 (APP. FEB. 21, 1812) TO PROVIDE APPROPRIATIONS FOR THE GOVERNMENT, TO APPROPRIATE $100,000 FOR CONTINGENT EXPENSES OF FOREIGN INTERCOURSE.
TO ORDER ENGROSSMENT AND THIRD READING OF H.R. 69, (APP. MAR. 14, 1812) TO AUTHORIZE A GOVERNMENT LOAN.
TO PASS H.R. 69, (APP. MAR. 14, 1812) TO AUTHORIZE A GOVERNMENT LOAN.
TO CONCUR IN THE FIRST WAR TAX RESOLUTION, TO INCREASE DUTIES ON IMPORTS.
TO POSTPONE CONSIDERATION OF THE WAR TAX RESOLUTION.
TO CONCUR IN THE SECOND WAR TAX RESOLUTION, THAT 25% BE RETAINED ON ALL DRAWBACKS ALLOWED BY LAW ON EXPORTATION OF UNITED STATES GOODS.
TO CONCUR IN THE THIRD WAR TAX RESOLUTION TO LEVY A TAX OF $1.25 PER TON ON ENTRY OF ALL FOREIGN VESSELS.
TO AGREE TO THE AMENDMENT OF THE FOURTH WAR TAX RESOLUTION, WHICH AMENDMENT WOULD REDUCE THE PROPOSED TAX ON IMPORTED SALT.
TO CONCUR IN THE FOURTH WAR TAX RESOLUTION, TO LAY A DUTY OF TWENTY CENTS ON IMPORTED SALT.
TO RECONSIDER THE VOTE ON THE FOURTH WAR TAX RESOLUTION, TO LAY A DUTY OF 20 CENTS ON IMPORTED SALT.
TO CONCUR IN THE FOURTH WAR TAX RESOLUTION, TO LAY A TAX OF TWENTY CENTS ON IMPORTED SALT.
TO RECOMMIT THE WAR TAX RESOLUTIONS TO COMM. OF THE WHOLE HOUSE.
TO ADOPT THE FIFTH WAR TAX RESOLUTION, TO LAY DUTIES ON LICENSES TO DISTILL SPIRITS, AT SET RATES.
TO ADOPT THE 6TH WAR TAX RESOLUTION TO LAY DUTIES ON LICENSES TO RETAILERS OF WINE, SPIRITS AND FOREIGN MERCHANDISE.
TO ADOPT THE 7TH WAR TAX RESOLUTION TO LAY DUTIES ON AUCTION SALE OF FOREIGN MERCHANDISE.
TO ADOPT THE 8TH WAR TAX RESOLUTION, TO LAY A DUTY ON ALL SUGAR REFINED IN THE U.S., ALLOWING A DRAWBACK ON EXPORTA- TION OF SAME.
TO ADOPT THE NINTH WAR TAX RESOLUTION TO LAY A DUTY ON CARRIAGES USED FOR THE CONVEYANCE OF PEOPLE.
TO ADOPT THE FIRST PART OF THE 10TH WAR TAX RESOLUTION PROVIDING TO TAX BANK NOTES PAYABLE TO BEARER ORDER.
TO ADOPT THE SECOND PART OF THE 10TH WAR TAX RESOLUTION, WHICH IS TO TAX ALL ENDORSED NOTES OF HAND AND BILLS OF EXCHANGE.  (P. 1107, 1151)
TO ADOPT THE ELEVENTH WAR TAX RESOLUTION, TO RAISE THREE MILLION DOLLARS BY DIRECT TAX AND APPORTIONED AMONG THE STATES AS PRESCRIBED BY THE CONSTITUTION.
TO ADOPT THE TWELVTH WAR TAX RESOLUTION, TO ALLOW THE STATES CERTAIN REDUCTIONS IN THE PAYMENT OF THE DIRECT TAX.
TO ADOPT THE THIRTEENTH WAR TAX RESOLUTION, THAT TAXES LAID WILL NOT TAKE EFFECT UNTIL AFTER THE U.S. SHALL HAVE BECOME ENGAGED IN A WAR WITH A NATION.
TO ADOPT THE FOURTEENTH WAR TAX RESOLUTION THAT TAXES SHALL CONTINUE NO LONGER THAN ONE YEAR AFTER THE CONCLUSION OF THE WAR.
TO AGREE TO THE ENTIRE SET OF WAR TAX RESOLUTIONS.
TO CONCUR IN THE SENATE AMENDMENT TO H.R. 25 (APP. MAR. 10, 1812) TO MAKE APPROPRIATIONS FOR THE DEFENSE OF MARITIME FRONTIERS, TO REDUCE THE APPROPRIATION FROM $1 MILLION TO $500,000.

TO GRANT TO THE COMM. ON FOREIGN RELATIONS, THE POWER TO SEND FOR WITNESSES AND PAPERS, IN ORDER THAT THEY MAY FURTHER INVESTIGATE A MESSAGE FROM THE PRESIDENT OF THE U.S., RELATING TO AN AGENT OF THE GOVERNMENT TRYING TO FOMENT DISAFFECTION TO THE CONSTTUTED AUTHORITIES OF THE NATION, AND ENDEAVORING TO ANNEX THE EASTERN PART OF THE U.S
TO PASS H.R. 65, A BILL FOR THE RELIEF OF GENERAL ST. CLAIR.
TO RECONSIDER THE VOTE ON PASSAGE OF H.R. 81 TO PROVIDE FOR THE REMOVAL OF CAUSES DEPENDING IN THE RESPECTIVE DISTRICT COURTS IN CASE OF DISABILITY OF THE JUDGES THEREOF.
TO AMEND THE BILL TO REPEAL THE TENTH SECTION OF THE ACT TO INCORPORATE THE SUBSCRIBERS TO THE BANK OF THE U.S., SO AS TO DECLARE THE ACT AS HAVING EXPIRED MARCH 4, 1811.

TO AMEND H.R. 29, A BILL FOR THE ADMISSION OF MISSISSIPPI INTO THE UNION, BY PROVIDING THAT NO GRANT, DEED, OR OTHER CONVEYANCE DERIVED FROM ANY AUTHORITY BE READ IN EVIDENCE IN ANY COURT OF SAID STATE AGAINST ANY GRANT DERIVED FROM U.S., UNLESS VALIDITYOF SAME HAS BEEN RECOGNIZED.
TO ORDER ENGROSSMENT AND 3RD READING OF H.R. 29.
TO PASS H.R. 29.

TO AMEND S. 9, (APP. MAY 22, 1812), A BILL TO ESTABLISH A QUARTERMASTER'S DEPARTMENT, BY ELIMINATING THAT PART OF BILL WHICH ESTABLISHES THE OFFICE OF COMMISSARY GENERAL, IN LIEU OF THE OFFICE OF SURVEYOR OF PUBLIC SUPPLIES.  THE OFFICE OF SURVEYOR IS ABLISHED BY S
TO AMEND S. 9 (APP. MAY 22, 1812) A BILL TO ESTABLISH A QUARTERMASTER DEPARTMENT, BY REDUCING THE PROPOSED SALARY OF COMMISSARY GENERAL FROM $3000 TO $2000 PER YEAR.
TO PASS H.R. 88 (APP. APR. 9, 1812, 2 STAT 701) TO ADMIT LOUISIANA INTO THE UNION AND TO EXTEND THE LAWS OF THE U.S. THERETO.

TO AGREE TO THE FIRST CLAUSE OF THE SENATE AMENDMENT TO H.R. 81, A BILL PROVIDING FOR THE REMOVAL OF CAUSES DEPENDING IN THE RESPECTIVE DISTRICT COURTS OF THE U.S. IN CASE OF DISABILITY OR ABSENCE OF THE JUDGES THEREOF. THE LANGUAGE IN QUESTION PROVIDES HAT IN CASES OF DISABILITY OF THE DISTRICT JUDGE, CERTIFIED TO THE SATISFACTION OF THE PRESIDENT OF THE U.S., THE CIRCUIT JUDGE SHALL HOLD THE DISTRICT COURT.
TO AGREE TO THE REMAINDER OF THE SENATE AMENDMENT TO H.R. 81 WHICH PROVIDES TO ALLOW THE SAID JUSTICES COMPENSATION OF $10 FOR EACH DAY OF SUCH SERVICE.
TO PASS THE RESOLUTION TO DIRECT THE ATT. GENERAL TO REPORT TO THIS HOUSE WHETHER THE PENAL CODE REQUIRES ALTERATION.
TO ADJOURN.
TO PASS H.R. 93 (APP. APR. 23, 1812) FOR THE RELIEF OF WILLIAM HUBBELL.

TO AMEND A RESOLUTION TO COMMIT NATHANIEL ROUSAVELT TO CUSTODY OF SERGEANT OF ARMS TO BE CONFINED, AND RESTRICTED FROM CONVERSATION WITH ALL PERSONS EXCEPT SERGEANT OF ARMS; WHICH AMENDMENT ELIMINATES THE CLAUSE RESTRICTING THE CONVERSATION OF ROUSAVELT. (P

TO AMEND THE RESOLUTION CONCERNING THE PROCEEDINGS REGARDING NATHANIEL ROUSAVELT, SO AS TO DISCHARGE HIM FROM CUSTODY SINCE HE HAS ANSWERED ALL QUESTIONS, BUT TO CONTINUE THE INVESTIGATION AS A RESULT OF HIS ANSWERS.
TO OVER-RIDE THE VETO OF H.R. 81, A BILL TO PROVIDE FOR REMOVAL OF CAUSES DEPENDING IN U.S. DISTRICT COURTS, IN CASE OF DISABILITY OR ABSENCE OF JUDGES THEREOF.
TO POSTPONE, INDEFINITELY H.R. 46, A BILL TO AUTHORIZE IMPORTATION OF GOODS, UNDER CERTAIN CIRCUMSTANCES, FROM GREAT BRITAIN, HER COLONIES, OR DEPENDENCIES.
TO APPOINT A COMMITTEE TO JOIN WITH A SENATE COMMITTEE, AND CONSIDER WHETHER A PROPOSED RECESS FROM ABOUT APRIL 20TH TO JUNE 15TH BE COMPATABLE WITH THE PUBLIC INTEREST.
TO CONCUR IN THE AMENDMENT TO S. 16, A BILL TO INCORPORATE THE LOUISIANA LEAD COMPANY, WHICH AMENDMENT ELIMINATES THE FIRST SECTION, AND THEREBY DEFEATS THE PURPOSE OF THE BILL.

TO AMEND H.R. 107 (APP. MAY 14, 1812) TO MAKE FURTHER PROVISIONS FOR THE U.S. ARMY, TO ELIMINATE THE SECTION AUTHORIZING THE PRESIDENT TO APPOINT TWO MAJOR GENERALS AND FOUR BRIGADIER GENERALS WHENEVER HE SHALL DEEM IT NECESSARY.

TO TABLE THE PETITION FROM CITIZENS OF THE STATE OF NEW YORK WHO ARE CONCERNED IN BUYING AND SELLING GRAIN, STATING THAT THEY HAVE IMMENSE QUANTITIES IN STORE FOR FOREIGN MARKETS, WHICH THEY ARE PREVENTED FROM EXPORTING DUE TO EMBARGO ACT; AND THAT BEFOR THE EXPIRATION OF THE ACT, THE GRAIN WILL HAVE SPOILED, AND PRAYING THAT SAID EMBARGO BE WHOLLY REPEALED OR THAT ITS DURATION BE SHORTENED.
TO POSTPONE THE PETITION FROM GRAIN DEALERS IN THE STATE OF NEW YORK, OBJECTING TO THE EMBARGO ACT WHICH PREVENTS THEM FROM EXPORTING THEIR GRAIN.

TO AMEND S. 4 (APP. APR. 29, 1812) TO MAKE FURTHER PROVISION FOR THE CORPS OF ENGINEERS, BY ADDING CLAUSE GIVING THE PRESIDENT AUTHORITY TO SUPPLY THE APPROPRIATION FOR THE ERECTION OF AN ADDITIONAL BUILDING AT SUCH PLACES AS HE MAY DESIGNATE.
TO AMEND S. 4, A BILL TO ESTABLISH A MILITARY ACADEMY IN PENNSYLVANIA, RATHER THAN WEST POINT.
TO AMEND S. 4, SO AS TO AUTHORIZE AN EXPENDITURE OF MONEY FOR PUBLIC BUILDINGS WITHIN THE DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA.
TO PASS H.R. 107 (APP. MAY 14, 1812), A BILL MAKING PROVISION FOR THE U.S. ARMY.
TO POSTPONE THE JOINT RESOLUTION TO ADJOURN CONGRESS FROM MAY 29 TO JUNE 8.
TO AMEND THE RECESS RESOLUTION TO CHANGE THE DATE OF ADJOURNMENT TO MAY 9.
TO POSTPONE INDEFINITELY, THE RESOLUTION RELATING TO RECESS OF CONGRESS.
TO ORDER ENGROSSMENT AND THIRD READING OF H.R. 74, A BILL FOR THE PROTECTION AND RECOVERY OF AMERICAN SEAMEN.

TO CONCUR IN THE AMENDMENT TO H.R. 105 TO MAKE FURTHER APPROPRIATIONS FOR SUPPORT OF THE GOVERNMENT FOR 1812, TO APPROPRIATE $40,000 FOR COMPENSATION TO MARSHALS AND ASSISTANT MARSHALS FOR TAKING AN ACCOUNT OF MANUFACTURE IN THE UNITED STATES.

TO AMEND THE RESOLUTION TO INSTRUCT A COMMITTEE TO REPORT A BILL FOR THE RELIEF OF THE INHABITANTS OF CARACAS AND TENERIFFE, BY ADDING A PROVISION TO GIVE CLEARANCE PAPERS TO SHIPS ENGAGED IN TRANSPORTING CERTAIN CARGO.
TO PASS THE FIRST PART OF THE CARACAS RESOLUTION, RELATING TO RELIEF MEASURES FOR VICTIMS OF AN EARTHQUAKE IN CARACAS.
TO PASS THE SECOND PART OF THE CARACUS RESOLUTION RELATING TO RELIEF FOR VICTIMS OF A LOCUST PLAGUE IN TENERIFFE.
TO PUT THE MAIN QUESTION ON PASSAGE OF THE JOINT RESOLUTION TO RECESS CONGRESS FROM MAY 6 TO MAY 25.
TO ORDER THIRD READING OF THE JOINT RESOLUTION TO RECESS CONGRESS FROM MAY 6 TO MAY 25.
TO PASS S. 31 SUPPLEMENTARY TO THE ACT "TO ESTABLISH AN EXECUTIVE DEPARTMENT, TO BE CALLED THE DEPARTMENT OF WAR."
TO POSTPONE CONSIDERATION OF THE PETITIONS ASKING FOR REPEAL OF THE EMBARGO ACT.

TO AMEND H.R. 12 (APP. MAY 22, 1812) TO ESTABLISH A QUARTERMASTERS DEPARTMENT, AND FOR OTHER PURPOSES, BY ELIMINATING THE SECTION GRANTING ADDITIONAL ALLOWANCES FOR RENT, FUEL, ETC., FOR VARIOUS DEPARTMENTS.
TO POSTPONE THE CONSIDERATION OF THE PETITIONS FOR A REPEAL OF THE EMBARGO ACT.

TO AMEND S. 33 A BILL TO ALLOW AN ANNUITY TO GENERAL ARTHUR ST. CLAIR, SO AS TO INCLUDE ALL OFFICERS AND SOLDIERS WHO SERVED IN THE REVOLUTIONARY WAR TO COMPENSATION IN ACCORDANCE TO THEIR RANK AND PAY.
TO ORDER THIRD READING OF S. 33, TO GRANT AN ANNUITY TO GENERAL ST. CLAIR.
******MISSING TEXT*******
TO POSTPONE, UNTIL JULY 4, THE PETITION OF JANNEY, NICHOLSON AND ROBINSON.
TO PROVIDE THAT WHEN THE HOUSE ADJOURN, IT DO SO UNTIL MONDAY.

TO CONCUR IN THE AMENDMENT TO H.R. 94 (APP. JULY 1, 1812) FOR THE RELIEF OF ANNA YOUNG, HEIRESS OF COL. JOHN DURKES, TO ELIMINATE THE CLAUSE CHARGING THE DEPRECIATION IN VALUE OF PAPER MONEY AGAINST THE CLAIM, AND TO PROVIDE FOR PAYMENT OF SAME.
TO PASS H.R. 94, (APP. JULY 1, 1812) FOR THE RELIEF OF ANNA YOUNG.
TO POSTPONE THE BILL RELATING TO ALLEGED SCARCITY OF PROVISIONS IN THE CANARY ISLANDS.
TO ORDER ENGROSSMENT AND THIRD READING OF S. 33, FOR THE RELIEF OF GENERAL ARTHUR ST. CLAIR.

TO SUSTAIN THE DECISION OF THE CHAIR THAT EVERY MOTION MUST BE SECONDED BEFORE IT CAN BE ANNOUNCED FROM THE CHAIR, AND MUST BE REDUCED TO WRITING; MOTION MADE DURING CONSIDERATION OF THE RESOLUTION PERTAINING TO RELATIONS BETWEEN THIS COUNTRY, GREAT BRITIN, AND FRANCE.
TO CONSIDER THE RESOLUTION THAT UNDER EXISTING CIRCUMSTANCES, IT IS INEXPEDIENT TO RESORT TO WAR AGAINST GREAT BRITAIN.
TO CONSIDER THE RESOLUTION REQUESTING INFORMATION PERTAINING TO OUR MILITARY PREPARATIONS, MEN, ENLISTED, VOLUNTEERS, STATE OF FORTIFICATIONS, ETC., FROM THE SEC. OF WAR.
TO CONCUR IN THE REPORT OF THE COMM. OF CLAIMS CONCERNING THE BILL FOR THE RELIEF OF AMY DARDEN, THAT SAID PETITION IS REASONABLE AND OUGHT TO BE GRANTED.

TO CONCUR IN THE REPORT OF THE COMM. OF ACCOUNTS CONCERNING EXPENDITURE OF THE CONTINGENT FUND OF THE HOUSE, TO PROVIDE THAT THE HOUSE CLERK BE ALLOWED A COMMISSION OF 2 1/2%, ON ALL MONEY DISBURSED BY HIM ON ACCOUNT OF CONTINGENT EXPENSES OF THE HOUSE, ROVIDED THAT THE TOTAL AMOUNT, ALLOWED SHALL NOT EXCEED $500 IN ANY ONE YEAR.
TO PASS H.R. 145, A BILL TO AUTHORIZE THE ISSUING OF TREASURY NOTES.

TO CONCUR IN AN AMENDMENT TO H.R. 128, (APP. JULY 1, 1812, 2 STAT L. 968) A BILL IMPOSING DUTIES UPON ALL GOODS IM- PORTED FROM ANY FOREIGN PART, WHICH AMENDMENT PROVIDES TO INCREASE THE DUTIES 100% ON ALL IMPORTED GOODS.
TO AMEND H.R. 128, TO PROVIDE THAT THIS ACT SHALL NOT GO INTO OPERATION UNTIL THE FIRST DAY OF NEXT SEPTEMBER.
TO AMEND H.R. 128, TO ELIMINATE THE ADDITIONAL DUTY OF 100% TO BE LEVIED UPON IMPORTED GOODS.
TO PASS H.R. 128.
TO POSTPONE INDEFINITELY THE RESOLUTION TO PARTIALLY SUSPEND, FOR A LIMITED TIME, THE SEVERAL ACTS PROHIBITING IMPORTATIONS FROM GREAT BRITAIN.
TO AMEND THE RESOLUTION RELATING TO SUSPENSION OF NON-IMPORTATION BY ELIMINATING THE FIRST SECTION OF THE BILL AND SUBSTITUTING A SECTION REPEALING ALL ACTS AS ENUMERATED.
TO AMEND THE RESOLUTION RELATING TO SUSPENSION OF NON-IMPORTATION, BY ELIMINATING ALL EXCEPTIONS, THEREBY MAKING THE SUSPENSION OF EMBARGO RELATIVE TO ALL IMPORTS.
TO POSTPONE UNTIL FEBRUARY 1, FURTHER CONSIDERATION OF A RESOLUTION TO SUSPEND NON-IMPORTATIONS.
TO RECONSIDER THE VOTE TO INDEFINITELY POSTPONE FURTHER CONSIDERATION OF A RESOLUTION SUSPENDING NON-INTERCOURSE.
TO PASS A RESOLUTION TO APPOINT A COMMITTEE TO BRING IN A BILL TO REPEAL AN ACT CONCERNING COMMERCIAL INTERCOURSE BETWEEN U.S., GREAT GRITAIN, FRANCE, AND DEPENDENCIES.
TO PASS THE FIRST SECTION OF A RESOLUTION, WHICH FIRST SECTION POSTPONES UNTIL THE FIRST MONDAY IN NOVEMBER, CONSIDERATION OF THE SEVERAL TAX BILLS REPORTED BY THE COMMITTEE OF WAYS AND MEANS TODAY.
TO ADOPT THE SECOND PART OF A RESOLUTION, WHICH PROVIDES FOR THE PRINTING OF TAX BILLS NOW BEING HELD FOR LATER DISPOSITION.
